<CaseStudy slug="operation-hired">
  <p class="lead reveal">A modern job search drowns in volume: thousands of postings, most irrelevant, many low-quality or outright fraudulent. Operation Hired is the engine I built to cut through it — a pipeline that ingests, scores, and ranks postings so attention goes to the few that are worth it.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What it does</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It pulls job postings into a local <code>SQLite</code> store, runs each through a scoring model, and surfaces a ranked shortlist. Across the live pool it has scored <strong>5,905 postings</strong>, with every score reproducible and re-runnable from source. The interesting part isn't the ranking — it's everything built to make the ranking <em>trustworthy</em>.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">How scoring works</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Tiering.</strong> Postings are bucketed by fit (role, seniority, comp signal). An early version over-inflated the top tier; I de-inflated it so "tier 1" actually means tier 1 — the count dropped from thousands to ~100.</li>
    <li><strong>Geo-matching.</strong> Location is checked against the target region so remote-mislabeled and wrong-metro postings don't pollute the shortlist.</li>
    <li><strong>Fraud signals.</strong> Heuristics flag the patterns of ghost and scam listings, cutting flagged-fraud noise by ~80%.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Built to be trusted, not just to run</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The system treats its own data as a liability to be audited, not a result to be assumed:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>A re-score pipeline</strong> re-evaluated all 5,905 rows against the corrected model in one pass with <strong>zero errors</strong>, backed up before it ran.</li>
    <li><strong>A 95-case test suite</strong> covers the scoring edges, geo logic, and fraud heuristics — green before any change ships.</li>
    <li><strong>Data-hygiene guards</strong> purge orphaned stress-test rows and block half-formed records from advancing through the pipeline.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why it's the artifact I point to</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It's a small, honest example of operations engineering: a data pipeline that makes decisions at scale, knows where it can be wrong, and proves its own correctness with tests and reproducible re-runs. That posture — <strong>evidence over assertion</strong> — is how I build everything.</p>
</CaseStudy>
